{"id":"1511.08163","submitter":"Shahab Haghi","authors":"Sh. Haghi, H.R. Maimani, A. Seify","title":"Star-critical Ramsey number of $K_4$ versus $F_n$","comments":"11 pages, 3 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  For two graphs $G$ and $H$, the Ramsey number $r(G,H)$ is the smallest\npositive integer $r$, such that any red/blue coloring of the edges of the graph\n$K_r$ contains either a red subgraph that is isomorphic to $G$ or a blue\nsubgraph that is isomorphic to $H$. Let $S_k=K_{1,k}$ be a star of order $k+1$\nand $K_n\\sqcup S_k$ be a graph obtained from $K_n$ by adding a new vertex $v$\nand joining $v$ to $k$ vertices of $K_n$. The star-critical Ramsey number\n$r_*(G,H)$ is the smallest positive integer $k$ such that any red/blue coloring\nof the edges of graph $K_{r-1}\\sqcup S_k$ contains either a red subgraph that\nis isomorphic to $G$ or a blue subgraph that is isomorphic to $H$, where\n$r=r(G,H)$. In this paper, it is shown that $r_*(F_n,K_4)=4n+2$, where\n$n\\geq{4}$.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 25 Nov 2015 19:10:28 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-11-26"}
